  {
    "slug": "what-camera-should-i-buy",
    "title": "What Camera Should I Buy? (The Honest Answer Nobody Wants to Hear)",
    "category": "cameras",
    "date": "2026-02-17",
    "readTime": "7 min read",
    "metaDescription": "The most common question I get. The honest answer: the camera is the last thing you should be thinking about. Here's what actually makes video look good — and then the cameras worth buying.",
    "excerpt": "Everyone asks what camera to buy. Here's the answer — and why you're asking the wrong question first.",
    "image": "/images/blog/canon-eos-r6-mark-ii-hero.jpg",
    "affiliateLink": "https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09JZT6YKL?tag=disbrowproduc-20",
    "relatedProducts": [],
    "content": "<p>It's the most common question I get. Someone's building their first setup, they've got a budget, and the first thing they want to know is what camera to buy. I understand the instinct. The camera feels like the foundation everything else is built around.</p>\n\n<p>But here's the thing: the camera is responsible for maybe 20% of how your video looks. The lens is another 30%. The lighting is the other 50%. People get this backwards constantly — they drop $3,000 on a body, put a kit lens on it, point it at a ring light, and wonder why it doesn't look like the videos they're trying to match.</p>\n\n<h2>What Are You Actually Doing With It?</h2>\n\n<p>This question completely changes the recommendation. Live streaming into an ATEM switcher has different requirements than YouTube content creation. A church adding a second camera has different needs than a solo creator. Be specific — the camera that's perfect for live production can be wrong for run-and-gun work.</p>\n\n<h2>Entry-Level: Canon R50V</h2>\n\n<p>If you're just starting out, the <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Canon+EOS+R50V&tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Canon EOS R50V</a> is the honest entry point. Canon built it specifically for video creators — clean HDMI out for live streaming, 4K video, compact and affordable. If you're not ready to spend $1,400+ on a Sony body, start here.</p>\n\n<h2>For Live Streaming and Production</h2>\n\n<p>If you're feeding into a switcher, the spec that matters most is clean HDMI or SDI output. The <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0C5GCGJG3?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Sony a6700</a> and <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0BHKL3GZL?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Sony FX30</a> are both strong production cameras — clean output, solid video performance, handles extended run times without overheating.</p>\n\n<p>For professional multicam live production with full Blackmagic integration, the <a href=\"https://atemschool.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Blackmagic Studio Camera</a> is a different category entirely. Talkback, tally, and full camera control run over a single SDI or fiber cable back to the ATEM. If you're building a real production system, this is the camera that makes it work the way it's supposed to. <a href=\"https://atemschool.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">ATEM School members get direct reseller pricing on Studio Cameras</a> — significantly better than retail.</p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B08WHJQPK7?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">BMPCC 6K Pro</a> is for cinema-quality work in a Blackmagic workflow — raw or ProRes output, native ATEM integration. Not an entry-level choice, but the right call if you're building that system.</p>\n\n<h2>For Content Creation and YouTube</h2>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09JZRWRJN?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Sony a7 IV</a> and <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0BL7X3KLV?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Canon EOS R6 Mark II</a> are the workhorses of this category. Full-frame, 4K, clean HDMI, a lens ecosystem worth investing in. Both pull double duty for live production if you need them to.</p>\n\n<p>If full-frame is out of budget, the <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0C5GCGJG3?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Sony a6700</a> is the best APS-C option — same E-mount as Sony's full-frame bodies, so every lens you buy transfers to a future upgrade.</p>\n\n<h2>The Budget Allocation Nobody Talks About</h2>\n\n<p>If you have $2,000: $600–800 on the body, $700–900 on a quality prime lens — the <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Sony+35mm+f1.8+OSS&tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Sony 35mm f/1.8</a> or Canon equivalent — and $300–500 on a key light.</p>\n\n<p>A $700 body with a $700 prime and proper lighting beats a $2,000 camera with a kit lens every time. The lens controls depth of field and how light renders. The body is the least important variable once you're past basic quality thresholds — and every major brand cleared that bar several generations ago.</p>\n\n<h2>The Short Answer</h2>\n\n<p>Entry-level: <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Canon+EOS+R50V&tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Canon R50V</a>. APS-C all-rounder: <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0C5GCGJG3?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Sony a6700</a>. Full-frame hybrid: <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B09JZRWRJN?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Sony a7 IV</a> or <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0BL7X3KLV?tag=disbrowproduc-20\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Canon R6 Mark II</a>. Live production / Blackmagic ecosystem: <a href=\"https://atemschool.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Blackmagic Studio Camera</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Then put the rest of the budget into glass and light. That's where the image actually comes from.</p>"
  }
